{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.5,0.09,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/115"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44325"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old woman presents with a 12 hour history of increasing confusion and lethargy. Her nursing home staff report she did not feel like getting out of bed and seemed less responsive than usual. She has Alzheimer disease and hypertension. She also has chronic urinary incontinence for which she has an indwelling urinary catheter. Her regular medications include donepezil, memantine, and ramipril. Her temperature is 38.0\u00b0C, pulse 109/min, respiratory rate 18/min and blood pressure 108/76 mmHg. She is only oriented to person and appears drowsy. She has some suprapubic and left renal angle tenderness. A plain abdominal X-ray shows a 4 mm stone at the left renal pelvico-ureteric junction. Her laboratory results are shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely to be responsible for her current condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proteus mirabilis","Escherichia coli","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Staphylococcus saprophyticus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract infections are the second most common type of infection encountered in long term residential care facilities and are usually seen in patients with chronic indwelling bladder catheters. Whilst \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E is the organism most usually associated with urinary tract infections, the presence of urolithiasis in this case suggests that the likely responsible organism is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EProteus mirabilis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E. This organism is a common cause of catheter-associated urinary infections. It is a Gram-negative rod, facultatively anaerobic, and produces the enzyme urease. This urease activity converts urea in the urine into ammonia, leading to alkalinisation of the urine, often with pH upwards of 8.0. Alkalinised urine also facilitates magnesium ammonium phosphate precipitates (i.e. struvite stones) which can form kidney stones - which in this case was confirmed on the abdominal X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae is another cause of catheter associated urinary tract infections, and is also associated with mildly alkaline urinary pH as it produces small amounts of urease, the enzyme responsible for the conversion of urea into ammonia. However, it typically does not present with urinary pH levels above 8 and is only associated with nephrolithiasis in rare cases. Pseudomonas aeruginosa is also commonly associated with catheter associated infections, especially due to its ability to form biofilms that are resistant to antibiotic therapy. However, it does not cause alkaline urine and only rarely causes struvite nephrolithiasis. Staphylococcus saprophyticus is a common cause of urinary tract infections in young, sexually active women, but is uncommon in older and/or catheterised patients. Also, it does not cause alkalinisation of urine nor does it predispose towards the development of kidney stones. Additionally, staphylococcal species are unable to reduce nitrate to nitrite hence the urinary nitrite levels will be negative if it were to be a staphylococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Proteus mirabilis is a urea-splitting organism that promotes the formation of urinary tract stones"],"references":["Nicolle LE. Urinary Tract Infections in the Older Patient. Clin Geriatr Med 2016; 32:523-38."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17486"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17486"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e41f4c6d-7757-4a4b-a1a2-206df84a2cb3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e41f4c6d-7757-4a4b-a1a2-206df84a2cb3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":499,"height":114}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40850"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T17:21:06+10:30","update